content.text:
The issue was that `WrappingRule` was incorrectly forcing a newline after the opening brace `{` of a lambda when the lambda body contained newlines (or was multiline), even if the lambda parameters were on the same line as the opening brace. This resulted in unexpected formatting, especially pushing the parameters to a new line and causing weird indentation.

The root cause was twofold:
1. `getStartOfBlock` method in `WrappingRule` failed to correctly identify the opening brace (`LBRACE`) of a `FUNCTION_LITERAL` (lambda) when parameters were present, because it stopped looking backwards at the arrow (`ARROW`). This prevented `beforeVisitBlock` from running for such lambdas.
2. Even if `beforeVisitBlock` ran, it enforced a newline after the `LBRACE` whenever the block contained a newline (`hasNewLineInClosedRange`), without checking if the layout should be preserved (i.e., parameters on the same line).

To fix this, I:
1. Updated `getStartOfBlock` to explicitly handle `FUNCTION_LITERAL` by looking for its `LBRACE` child, ensuring `beforeVisitBlock` correctly identifies the start of the lambda block.
2. Modified `beforeVisitBlock` to skip enforcing the newline after `LBRACE` if the lambda parameters (or arrow) immediately follow the brace on the same line. This is implemented in the new `shouldPreserveLambdaLayout` helper method.

This ensures that:
- Single-line lambdas are preserved.
- Lambdas with parameters on the same line as the opening brace (e.g., `{ size -> ... }`) are preserved, even if the body is multiline.
- Lambdas with parameters on separate lines (e.g., `{ a,\n b -> ... }`) still enforce the newline after the brace, which is the desired behavior for multiline parameters.

I verified the fix with reproduction tests covering these scenarios.

